22,'_vfb_field-29','They/them'),(453,222,'_vfb_field-30','Yes'),(454,222,'_vfb_field-31','Nonbinary'),(455,222,'_vfb_field-28','1986'),(456,222,'_vfb_field-25','(541) 731-4007'),(457,222,'_vfb_field-26','ospreyhealing@gmail.com'),(458,222,'_vfb_field-27','Email'),(459,222,'_vfb_field-32','<U>Other</U>...'),(460,222,'_vfb_field-33','<p>Are you aware that the DMV does not guarantee new photos when you change your gender marker (or if you change anything else on your license, for that matter) for folks age 30 and up? That decision is made at the manager\'s discretion at whichever local DMV you go to. People may be able to get their photos changed in some locations if the manager agrees with it, if their face is visibly very different than before, if they\'ve had facial reconstructive  surgery, if they\'ve lost or gained  a bunch of weight, or if their 8-year renewal cycle is up. But unfortunately, in most situations like this, discretion = oppression, and if the particular DMV manager on duty is in any way unsupportive or uneducated on Trans & gender diverse matters, folks could still end up with an ID card that is unrepresentative of their identity, outs them, and opens them up to the possibility of discrimination and violence.</p>\n<p>I\'m very glad we\'ve won the right to represent ourselves more accurately with the X gender marker. But I think we still need to push for accurate photo representation as well. Does Basic Rights Oregon know about this issue?</p>\n<p>Osprey</p>\n'),(461,222,'_vfb_field-41',''),(462,222,'_vfb_field-42',''),(463,222,'_vfb_field-34',''),(464,222,'_vfb_field-35',''),(465,223,'_wp_attached_file','2016/11/tae-e1502472219550.jpg'),(466,223,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:5:{s:5:\"width\";i:8;s:6:\"height\";i:11;s:4:\"file\";s:30:\"2016/11/tae-e1502472219550.jpg\";s:5:\"sizes\";a:8:{s:9:\"thumbnail\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:15:\"tae-150x150.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:150;s:6:\"height\";i:150;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}s:6:\"medium\";a:4:{s:4:\"